4. Model Building¶

Before implementing the KNN Model we would want to¶

  1. Encode the Class column using label encoder
  2. Tune the data as we know KNN is prone to outliers
  3. Impute the outliers with median
  4. Standardize the features useing ZScore i.e normalize the data to not have errors in distance caculation in KNN
In [35]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier

from scipy.stats import zscore

5. Performance Improvement:¶

A. Experiment with various parameters to improve performance of the base model.¶

In [44]:
myList = list(range(1,50))
neigh = list(filter(lambda x: x % 2 != 0, myList))
ac_scores = []
for k in neigh:
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k)
    knn.fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_pred = knn.predict(X_test)
    scores = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    ac_scores.append(scores)
MSE = [1 - x for x in ac_scores]
optimal_k = neigh[MSE.index(min(MSE))]
print("The optimal number of neighbours is %d" % optimal_k)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
plt.plot(neigh, MSE)
plt.xlabel('Number of neigh K')
plt.ylabel('Misclassification Error')
plt.show()

The optimal number of neighbours is 11

Observations

It can be inferres from teh eblow method above that the optimal K value for this dataset is 11

In [45]:
knn_new_best = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors= 11 , weights = 'distance' )
knn_new_best.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred = knn_new_best.predict(X_test)
print('Accuracy for K=11:', accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred) )
print('Recall for K=11:', recall_score(y_test, y_pred, average= 'weighted') )
print('Precision for K=11:', precision_score(y_test, y_pred, average= 'weighted'))
predicted_labels = knn_new_best.predict(X_test)
knn_new_best.score(X_test, y_test)
cm=metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, predicted_labels, labels=[0,1,2])
df_cm = pd.DataFrame(cm, index = [i for i in ["Normal","Type_H","Type_S"]],
                  columns = [i for i in ["Predict Normal","Predict Type_H", "Predict Type_S"]])

plt.figure(figsize = (7,5))
sns.heatmap(df_cm, annot=True)

l1 = list(range(1,70))
neighbors = list(filter(lambda x: x % 2 != 0, l1))
In [112]:
ac_scores = []
for k in neighbors:
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k)
    knn.fit(X_train_smt, y_train_smt)
    y_pred = knn.predict(X_test)
    scores = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    ac_scores.append(scores)
MSE = [1 - x for x in ac_scores]
optimal_k = neighbors[MSE.index(min(MSE))]
print("The optimal number of neighbours is %d" % optimal_k)

The optimal number of neighbours is 1
